<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-410-860  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 410 860.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  April 30 1990 n298 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Net helps Feds. (Financial Crimes Enforcement Network aids federalinvestigators)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Jackson, Kelly.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Financial Crimes Enforcement Network, (FinCEN), anorganization formed by the US Treasury Department, began operatingin Mar 1990 as part of the Bush administration's anti-drugcampaign.andP;  FinCen was designed as a technology-driven program thattracks and analyzes suspicious financial transactions associatedwith drug-trafficking, organized crime and white-collar crime.andO;Investigators from several law enforcement agencies serve on theorganization's staff.andP;  FinCEN, which operates as a supportorganization, combines information from law-enforcement databasesto come up with leads.andP;  The system includes a local area network(LAN) of Apollo Computer Domain workstations and expert-systemsoftware.andP;  FinCEN also operates another LAN database that includesfacts on suspects.andP;  FinCEN connects to other federal databasesthrough dedicated lines; other organizations cannot access FinCEN.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Apollo Computer Inc. (products).andO;Product:   Apollo Domain (Workstation) (usage).andO;Topic:     NetworksFinancial Crimes Enforcement Network (Computer network)InvestigationsExpert SystemsData BasesDrug AbuseUnited States. Department of the TreasuryLaw Enforcement.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>